WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.500
WCAG stands for Web Content Accessibility Guidelines.

00:00:04.500 --> 00:00:11.000
It is an international standard for making web content more accessible to people with disabilities.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:19.000
These guidelines help ensure that websites can be used by a wide range of users, including those with visual,
auditory, physical, speech, cognitive, and neurological disabilities.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:23.000
WCAG is organized around four main principles.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:24.500
Perceivable.

00:00:24.500 --> 00:00:33.000
Information and user interface components must be presented in ways users can perceive.
This includes providing text alternatives for images and captions for multimedia.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:34.500
Operable.

00:00:34.500 --> 00:00:45.500
User interface components and navigation must be usable.
This means users should be able to interact with content using a keyboard and have enough time to read and use content.

00:00:45.500 --> 00:00:47.000
Understandable.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:57.500
Information and operation of the user interface must be understandable.
Content should be clear, predictable, and easy to follow.

00:00:57.500 --> 00:00:59.000
Robust.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:08.000
Content must be robust enough to work with a wide range of technologies,
including assistive technologies like screen readers.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:13.000
WCAG also includes different levels of conformance.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:17.000
Level A is the minimum level of accessibility.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:21.500
Level AA is the level most organizations aim to meet.

00:01:21.500 --> 00:01:26.000
Level AAA is the highest level of accessibility.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:32.000
Following WCAG helps create a more inclusive web experience for everyone.